<article>
    <h1>NEW MENU RESTAU&#xAD;RANT GAIG</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201225/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-25"><time>2020-12-25</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE STYLE WEEKEND</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The four-year-old Restau­rant Gaig, known for its Cata­lan fare, has ex­panded its din­ing space in Stan­ley Street and re­freshed its menu.</p>
    <p>Some stand-out dishes show­case ex­ec­u­tive chef Marti Car­los</p>
    <p>Martinez’s in­no­va­tive flair.</p>
    <p>Start with the salmorejo soup ($17), a spin on clas­sic cold tomato soup with savoury ja­mon ice cream, tomato sponge and creamy bur­rata.</p>
    <p>I en­joy the Bomba de la Barcelonet­a ($15, above right), a deep-fried potato ball wrapped in a thin and crisp crust of squid ink bread­crumb. It is served with aioli and a spicy brava sauce which packs a de­li­cious punch.</p>
    <p>For mains, you will not re­gret or­der­ing ten­der char­coal-grilled oc­to­pus ($32.50) with cau­li­flower done in three ways – puree, pick­led, and roasted; and quail es­ca­betx ($32).</p>
    <p>The lat­ter draws on a cen­turies-old recipe where the quail is pre­served in a mari­nade of white wine vine­gar, with a touch of sherry vine­gar to soften its sharp­ness.</p>
    <p>Her­itage dishes – such as the sig­na­ture can­nel­loni ($16.50), with roast beef and pork wrapped in can­nel­loni sheets and served with a truf­fled cream sauce – re­main on the menu. Tra­di­tion­ally served dur­ing Christ­mas in Barcelona, the dish is – thank­fully – avail­able year-round here.</p>
    <p>WHERE Restau­rant Gaig, 16 Stan­ley Street</p>
    <p>MRT Telok Ayer</p>
    <p>OPEN Noon to 2pm, 6 to 10pm, Mon­days to Satur­days, closed on Sun­days</p>
    <p>TEL 6221-2134</p>
    <p>INFO sin­ga­pur.restau­rant­gaig.com</p>

